## 1. Eligibility (Scope data - Invent Format)

TB currently has a 3 pronged approach.  They use class (which is style). Planner does set up in green screen for product set up.

1. set up 'replenishment source': blank (if not replen), DC (if DC replenishment- DC is filling stores), V for vendor (a flow through (bulk from vendor, system does instant allocation, so it flows through( no backstock), or V- direct to store (for K&G).
2. then set up which colors are on replen, called model keys. They can do supersession links if they want.  But this is where they pick the colors of the styles they want replenished.
3. the store part- (called model base)- it is an eligibility screen for style/color/size at a store - A active, I inactive, D distribution only, O for order but not replen from DC (for more units for expansion to more stores)

IA next steps:

ly, O for order but not replen from DC (for more units for expansion to more stores)

They might have multiple supersede products. For 3g2t, 289L and 3t46 are the supersedes.

h primary.

They couldn’t start rpl unless they enter a min ss. They want to input max ss.

We need to give a suggestion system to them so that every time a new class color & product is introduced, we need to find a match class color for that to define forecast.

We need to do the NPI with class-color level.

They need to determine some parameters by authorization. Like Min SS. (May not be necessary) (37:00)

content: . fragrances are in 2’s but garment bags are in 100.For some Belt vendors - receive Available to Ship (ATS) periodically Approx 5 vendors send ATS every week, some send ATS every month, some do not have availability constraintsThese ATS units are being held specifically for TB, not available for other retailersATS units are based on vendor projections provided by TB Review to ensure they have sufficient stock to fulfil the orderDone to ensure we don’t tie up OTB on orders that cannot be fulfilled?? What would happen if we just let the order be raised and corrected the OTB when the order is confirmed? How long is the delay? Would be good if the system could constrain against Vendor’s ATS systematically, rather than user having to make these decisions manuallyRequest for ability to upload ATS into system, and for system to use to constrain against.There are usually unit driven minimums per supplier/store, however when products are < $1 to ~ $5 it is challenging to come up with a minimum

metadata.title: Vendor to Store and Flow Thru

content: supplier/store, however when products are < $1 to ~ $5 it is challenging to come up with a minimum unit quantity to targetE.g. Vendor Redstone has a $500 min cost constraint per storeUser needs to calculate “Cost per Door” and for stores that don’t make the threshold, delete the SOQsIf the order is approx $516, and the vendor is OOS of a couple of items, the order total will fall below the $500 min threshold and not be fulfilled This vendor does not provide ATSUser looks for order quantity to be between $580 and $650 to ensure this doesn’t happen!! If this does happen, the vendor cannot take the one store that doesn’t meet the min threshold off the order

Used to view the totals at the vendor level for Flow Through or Direct to Store from the vendor perspective.Configurable2.3Report: Vendor to Store Replenishment Dashboard. Used to review the total for Flow Through or Direct to Store from the store perspective.Configurable2.4Ability to review and edit initial allocation based on updated PO quantities / ASN Quantities. Ideally would have logic to systematically constrain the initial allocation quantities to the adjusted PO quantities, rather than requiring a user to manually adjust the order

ordered at least once a month, that cannot be handled in JDA because JDA can't accommodate prepacks. Requires user to manually allocate that product.Would want to replenish these in an ideal world!! ## 3- Transactional  Sales

The process of how the columns sent by the customer correspond to our schema can be seen in the table below. For example, the transaction_id sent by the customer corresponds to sales_id in our schema, and to create the transaction_id under operation, the product_code and transaction_id from the customer's data are combined.

Operation Table

1. Return transactions’ sales quantity and revenues are mapped as positive
2. transaction_id
3. sales_id

Raw Data

1. Return transactions’ sales quantity and revenues are coming as negative
2. transaction_id + product_code
3. transaction_id

ales quantity and revenues are coming as negative
2. transaction_id + product_code
3. transaction_id

In the raw data, each row is represented with either a +1 or -1 sales quantity. The sales data is reported in a disaggregated format, where each individual unit sold is represented as a separate row in the dataset, rather than aggregating the total quantity sold for each product. This means the raw data is not unique by date-store-product but is unique by transaction_id - line_item_id. During the mapping process, it is aggregated by transaction-id, sales_id, and sales_type at the operation level

## 5- PDSR ( Product Destination Source Relation)

When the PDSR table is created, two different tables are taken based on the Source type. Entries with source type 1 (warehouse) are taken from the pdsr_warehouse table, while those with source type 2 (supplier) are taken from the pdsr_supplier table. The schema of the input data for these tables are slightly different from each other . Screenshots of the inputs for these tables can be found below.

*PDSR-SupplierPDSR-Warehouse*

ther . Screenshots of the inputs for these tables can be found below.

*PDSR-SupplierPDSR-Warehouse*

As seen above, the pdsr_supplier table is received at a more granular level, whereas for the pdsr_warehouse table, processing needs to be done. The operations performed are as follows: First, the brand prefix is obtained by performing a substring operation on the destination_code column. Then, the data is joined with product_master based on brand and item_type, reducing it to the product_code level.Finally, because products associated with suppliers are also reflected in the table below, the shipment type table is used to eliminate these. Product codes with a shipment type equals to 1 are filtered out from the pdsr_warehouse table.

- Type 0 > Store
- Type 1 > Warehouse
- Type 2 > Supplier

## 6- Shipment Type

For the input of the Shipment Type table, only two columns are provided by the customer: product_code and shipment type. Each product has one shipment type, and unlike other customers, shipment_type 2 is used for flow-thru products by this customer. Because a store_id column is required in the shipment_type table under Operation, it is joined with the PDSR table to generate this

1- > DTS (Direct To Store) KNG Brand uses that, and it is from supplier to direct to store

2- > Flow Thru (Supplier To Store)

## 9- Open Orders

The input of the open orders table is as above. To transfer this under the operations table, we need to fill some columns. We fill the quantity_approved column with the incoming quantity_ordered column and fill other quantity columns with 0. Additionally, we currently fill the estimated arrival date column as null.

and we fill estimated arrival date as run_date + 1

## 10- Supplier Master

We receive two different types of `supplier_code` from our customer: one with 4 digits and another with 7 digits. The 7-digit codes are stored under `master-data/operations`, while the 4-digit codes, referred to as `merch_vendor`, are stored as an attribute in the `product_master` table. Yes, only one `merch_vendor` can be defined for each product. If you see `source_code` represented differently in various tables, don't be surprised. # C. Customized/Remarkable Operation Tables

In this section, customized tables under the operation category or notes that are considered beneficial to understand will be mentioned.

## 1- Scope

1.One-Time Scope

We already discussed the one-time scope above. The difference between the one-time scope and `final_scope`, which is the input for scope, is the additional data later provided by the customer. ([Details](https://invent.atlassian.net/browse/TBRCS-63))This can be found under `one_time_uploads` as `eligibility_extra`.

2.UI Scope

From the UI/parameter configuration page, the customer can input data for both `dc_rpl` and `store_rpl` across different dimensions (product, product-store, or store). All the inputs entered through the UI are first converted to the product-store or product-warehouse level. Then, they are combined with `final_scope` to create `operation/scope`.

or product-warehouse level. Then, they are combined with `final_scope` to create `operation/scope`.

Note Blocked Scope:

Blocked scope parameters entered through the UI are automatically applied by Rocket for `store_rpl`. For `dc_rpl`, they are excluded from the generated scope to use dc_rpl. Therefore, it is possible to see the blocked scope pairs under `operation/scope`.

The Extended Product table is used to store `program`and `sillhouette` information entered through the UI.

Under the Extended Store table, the `climate zone` information from the UI and the `district code` and `district description` from the daily flow are stored.

## 6- Lead Time

The Lead Time process actually involves two stages:

1. If the product is managed with order groups, their lead time information is stored under the operation/order_group/order_subgroup_constraints tables. The lead time for these products is retrieved by joining these tables.
2. The lead time generated in this way is then combined with the lead time from the daily flow to create operation/lead_time.

Reference Products section, you will see an arrow pointing to the Create button.Once you click Create, a panel will appear where you are required to enter two `product_code` values.

The first thing the system checks is whether the `size_code` values of the entered products are the same:

1. If the size_code values of the entered products are different, the system immediately reflects the given result for this product pair.
2. If the size_code values of the entered products are the same, the system then matches the size_code values based on the option_code(class-color) of the entered products. It reflects all matching size_code values to the system.

Below, you can find detailed examples for both scenarios:

Input:

Let’s assume that two `product_code` values are entered into the system. The system first checks the `product_master` data to determine whether the `size_code` values of these two `product_code` entries are the same or not.

to determine whether the `size_code` values of these two `product_code` entries are the same or not.

In this example, since the `size_code` values of the two entered `product_code` values are different, the system only matches these two products and reflects the result directly.

Now, consider the second scenario: What happens if the entered products share the same `size_code` values? Let’s assume that two `product_code` values have been entered into the system.

In this case, the first action the system takes is to retrieve all products associated with the `option_code` values of the entered products. After fetching these products, the system matches them based on their `size_code`. As a result, by entering only two `product_code` values, you can reference multiple products.

code`. As a result, by entering only two `product_code` values, you can reference multiple products.

As shown in the example above, since the `size_code` values of these two products are the same, all products that belong to the same `option_code` as these products are listed. Then, other products with the same `size_code` are also matched. In the example above, you can see that the rows with the same color are matched.

Finally, if you provideinput to the system as shown below:

The system returns a single row for TMW's products because they have different `size_code` values. However, for JAB's products, since they share the same `size_code` and there are multiple matching `size_code` values, the system returns as many rows as there are matching `size_code` values under that `option_code`.

8. Use Breakdown Forecast for Staggered ProductsMotivation:When a client launches a new product in a limited store rollout, then later expands distribution to additional stores, the LLTD model assigns a zero forecast to the newly added stores due to their lack of historical sales data. To address this, we propose using a breakdown forecast, allocating demand proportionally from existing, to generate non-zero forecasts for these new locations.Related Tasks: Related PRs:https://github.com/inventanalytics/customer-pipeline-tbretail/pull/494 https://github.com/inventanalytics/customer-pipeline-tbretail/pull/495 https://github.com/inventanalytics/customer-pipeline-tbretail/pull/498 https://github.com/inventanalytics/customer-pipeline-tbretail/pull/503 https://github.com/inventanalytics/customer-pipeline-tbretail/pull/506 https://github.com/inventanalytics/customer-pipeline-tbretail/pull/507 Notes:Staggered Items Forecast Notes

### Cheetah Fixeshttps://github.com/inventanalytics/customer-pipeline-tbretail/pull/507

1. Wrong data in the Summary page of Store Replenishment Orders screen for null aggregationsRelated discussion: https://invent-analytics.slack.com/archives/C02TUMUF15Z/p1732525360362869 Related Task:
2. Multiple reference store assignment problemRelated discussion: https://invent-analytics.slack.com/archives/C02TUMUF15Z/p1727255267665659 Related Task:
3. We can not upload big one time data (presentation stock) in the UI. As a result we prepared custom etl combining the big one time data with the UI uploaded data.
4. The visibility of the uploaded data is not enough so that we had to create a tableau report / report export for each type of upload data & parameter configuration data such as eligibility, supersede products, reference product/stores etc.

### ETL & Pre-ETL Extensions

metadata.title: Required Extensions/Fixes during the Project Implementation

content:
such as eligibility, supersede products, reference product/stores etc.

### ETL & Pre-ETL Extensions

1. Supersede and Reference Product relations are defined at the OptionCode level. However the Invent products supports only SKU level relationship definitions. Going up to the Option level is done with extension.
2. Purchase Order data format was not fitting to the data requirement format.
3. Product Destination Source Relationship is shared on Product-Source Level. The expansion of data required detailed analysis and extension
4. There was no ready etl scripts for the data upload data and new parameter configuration data.

### Other

1. Pagerduty is not calling for the errors received in the adhoc_output_dag that rises potential risk of writing the approved orders lately and nessecitates manual tracking of the dag.
2. Even all brand partition data are arrived the daily dag might not see it complete. It requires manual daily run start with given configs.

- Primary vs. Secondary SourceThe function extends existing orders (already allocated from primary distribution centers) with potential orders from a secondary DC. It only uses the secondary DC if the primary DC can’t fully meet remaining needs.
- Two New “Exclusion” ChecksBefore using a secondary DC, the function excludes cases where the item-destination pair is about to receive inventory from the primary DC anyway. Specifically, it checks:Open Purchase Orders (POs): If a PO will arrive within 10 days, skip the secondary DC.Goods in Transit (GIT): If there is in-transit inventory to arrive within 10 days, skip the secondary DC.
- Eliminating Some Secondary OrdersThe function merges these POs/GIT records to remove (or “eliminate”) item-store pairs from the secondary DC if the arrival from the primary DC is imminent.

“eliminate”) item-store pairs from the secondary DC if the arrival from the primary DC is imminent.
- Calculating Remaining Supply & NeedRemaining Supply: Takes total supply at each DC, subtracts any orders that have already been placed from the primary DC to see what’s left.Remaining Need: Takes each item-store’s “rounded need” and subtracts the quantity already satisfied by the primary DC.
- Secondary DC Ordering LogicOnly items with positive remaining need and DCs with remaining supply become candidates for secondary orders.Costs & Priorities: The function merges cost data and checks some “benefit” calculations, ensuring that only feasible casepack quantities are ordered.It groups items together, sorts by descending “benefit,” and ensures the secondary DC has enough supply for the cumulative orders.

s by descending “benefit,” and ensures the secondary DC has enough supply for the cumulative orders.
- Smart Window EliminationIf an item-store combination was excluded (due to an upcoming PO or GIT), the function tries to see if some partial portion of the secondary DC orders can be matched exactly (select_pairs_exact_sum) to meet that “expected” demand.Orders that fully exceed or match that “expected quantity” are eliminated from the secondary DC’s final orders.
- Final OutputThe function concatenates the primary DC orders (from order_quantity) with any secondary DC orders that survived all the filters and “smart window” checks.It also returns a DataFrame of the eliminated pairs (smart_window_eliminated) for reference or debugging.

so returns a DataFrame of the eliminated pairs (smart_window_eliminated) for reference or debugging.

Workflow that writes the eliminated results daily: [https://adb-1638025694947766.6.azuredatabricks.net/jobs/507341841112529?o=1638025694947766%3Fo%3D1638025694947766%3Fo%3D1638025694947766%3Fo%3D1638025694947766](https://adb-1638025694947766.6.azuredatabricks.net/jobs/507341841112529?o=1638025694947766%3Fo%3D1638025694947766%3Fo%3D1638025694947766%3Fo%3D1638025694947766) → This workflow is scheduled for the test purpose and shares the eliminated results with the client in the test environment. Since we agreed that the smart window logic works as expected it can be paused.

# Regular Controls:

Below list checks: performed manually 2 days a week via script ,not automated yet.

| Control | How do we do that | Why do we do that |
| --- | --- | --- |
| A - Metrics* Analyze (. below) | Metrics are calculated and compared to the previously measured benchmark. | Measuring the percentage of consecutive orders. |
| B - Inventory Position - Target Comprasion | The inventory position is calculated and compared against the target.If IP > Target,  ensure no orders | 1- IP calculation comparison with rocket2- Detect unnecessary orders |
| Open Orders Monitoring | Open orders from one day are compared with those from the previous day. | To identify pairs:Increased without a order Increased by more than the order that was placed. |
| Pair Analyze | G.I.T., P.O., O.O., and inventory values are examined for randomly selected pairs with consecutive orders. | 1- Understand the reason why was the order repeated?2- Analyze the above controls on the examples |

1- Understand the reason why was the order repeated?2- Analyze the above controls on the examples |

### A-Metrics* :

- The number of pairs ordered on a given day that were also ordered the previous day.
- The number of pairs ordered on a given day that had also been ordered within the past two weeks.
- The total number of unique pairs ordered in the last 2 consecutive weeks.

| % of ordered pairs  for 2 weeks straight | 0.22% |

## One Time Controls:

1. Rocket vs Operation IP tables: The Open Orders, GIT, and inventory columns calculated by Rocket were compared with those under the operation at the main item level.
2. Tables with Estimated Arrival Date: Additional checks were done in the G.I.T and PO tables to ensure that the root cause of this issue was not present in other relevant tables.
3. Creating a benchmark: We calculated the metrics identified each day during the one-week period before the fix (January 12–18, 2025) and the one-week period after the fix (February 9–15, 2025), then used these daily values to form an average benchmark.

This document outlines the data validation and consistency checks performed by the Input Controller for the brands JAB, KNG, MSP, and TMW. The controller verifies the completeness, integrity, and consistency of daily input files delivered by the client. It also compares numerical and transactional data to previous records to identify anomalies or significant changes.

### ✅ 1. File Arrival Check

- All expected input tables have been received for the day.
- Validation was conducted for each table under the following brands:JAB, KNG, MSP, TMW

This ensures no table is missing and the daily pipeline can proceed with complete input data.

### 📊 2. Table Count & Change Analysis

For each expected table, two main checks were performed:

a.

### 📊 2. Table Count & Change Analysis

For each expected table, two main checks were performed:

| Metric Category | Checks Applied |
| --- | --- |
| Row Count | Number of records in today's input |
| Change (%) | Percentage difference compared to yesterday |

### 📦 3. Transactional & Sales Summary Monitoring

For each brand (JAB, KNG, MSP, TMW), key transactional metrics and sales figures were validated to ensure data consistency and business logic continuity.

### 4. Max Value Threshold Monitoring

Tables containing numerical values were scanned for their maximum submitted values across the following fields:If any value exceeds a predefined [alert threshold](https://github.com/inventanalytics/customer-pipeline-tbretail/blob/main/rocks_extension/workflow_1/input_control.py#L584-L621), it is automatically highlighted in yellow to ensure visibility and prompt investigation.

## 📘 Output Controller – Daily Output Validation Report

### Overview

This document describes the daily rocket output validation process carried out by the Output Controller for the brands JAB, KNG, MSP, and TMW. The controller is designed to track the operational output trends across multiple days and source types to ensure output consistency and detect anomalies in generation patterns.

### 1. Output Trend Monitoring

The controller captures daily output metrics for each brand and `source_type`, including:

- run_date: The processing date
- brand: Brand name (JAB, KNG, MSP, TMW)
- source_type: 1 (e.g., DC to Store), 2 (e.g., Supplier to Store)
- target_date: Target shipment/delivery date
- output_quantity: Quantity generated as output
- unique_product_count: Number of distinct products involved
- unique_pair_count: Number of unique product-location combinations

metadata.title: Tailored Brands Retail Input Data Control Checklist

content:
er of distinct products involved
- unique_pair_count: Number of unique product-location combinations

These values are tracked over multiple days to enable visibility into generation patterns, production stability, and potential anomalies such as drops or spikes in output.

### 2. Trend Visualization

A [Tableau dashboard](https://tableau.inventanalytics.com/#/site/Tbretail/views/OutputControlInternal/OutputControl?:iid=1) is available for enhanced visibility. It provides:

- A 15-day trend view for each brand and source type
- Interactive graphs to spot daily fluctuations
- Quick filtering and comparison features

> 📎 You can access the dashboard directly via the “Click For Last 15 Days Tableau Report” link at the bottom of the report email.

# Rocket Default Alerts:

## Target Alerts

1- Target Alert Threshold:

The target alert threshold is an alert that takes input from any of the product, store, or product/store levels via the parameter configuration screen and applies it at the product/store level during post-optimization. It marks the output of target alerts that exceed the defined thresholds as "semi-approved" and throws a “`Target Exceeds User-Defined Threshold`” alert.
It directly apllies based on the customer’s inputs.

2- Average Target Alert:

The average target threshold alert operates without requiring any customer input, and its working mechanism is as follows:

1. It calculates the average of the previously computed target values over the past 30 days for the relevant pair.
2. If the current target exceeds this average target by a coefficient of 5 (Configurable Here), it triggers an “Target Spike Detected“ alert.

rage target by a coefficient of 5 (Configurable Here), it triggers an “Target Spike Detected“ alert.

However, in the current structure, this alert has no impact on the output and is used solely for informational purposes.

## Order Alerts

1- Order Alert Threshold:

The Order Alert Threshold follows the same logic as the Target Alert Threshold. It can take the customer’s input at any level and applies it during post-optimization by marking the pairs that exceed the threshold as “semi-approved.” and throws an “`Order Exceeds User-Defined Threshold`” alert.

## General Informations About Rocket Default Alerts:

### 1- Input Data Resolve

If a threshold alert has customer inputs defined at different dimensions, two factors in order are considered to resolve input:

1. Priority
2. Input timestamp

nt dimensions, two factors in order are considered to resolve input:

1. Priority
2. Input timestamp

If a pair has multiple inputs, the value from the input dimension with the higher priority is used. However, if the inputs have the same priority, the most recent one based on input timestamp is applied.

You can find the priority list [here](https://github.com/inventanalytics/customer-pipeline-tbretail/blob/5e445027f0dc72cbd7509ef75037c2560392afb6/rocks_extension/rocket_pandas/prep/alert_threshold.py#L81-L117)

## Parameters Configuration Features

Parameter Configurations:  This section allows users to manage all parameter settings. Users can view, filter, modify, export, or delete configurations. If needed, they can also activate or deactivate them based on business needs.

Configuration Detail: To review the details of a specific configuration, the user can select its Configuration ID to access comprehensive information, including parameter values, validity period, locations, and other attributes. If needed, they can make adjustments and save updates to ensure accuracy.

Create New Configuration: To create a new configuration, users can define key details such as scope, type, and validity period. Once set, they can fine-tune parameter values, apply bulk adjustments, and finalize updates to ensure seamless integration into the system.

- Every configuration is distinguished by a unique Configuration ID, and each configuration is created regarding a Solution Type and a scope. The level of granularity of the configuration can be viewed from the Scope column. The details on the creator user of the configurations, last update, and creation times can also be viewed.
- The configurations are valid as long as the durations between the Start Date - End Date. Once the End Date passes, the configuration becomes Passive. Until after the End Date or unless a user deactivates the Configuration ID, the configuration remains Active. The activity duration can be checked from the Remaining Days column in the view.
- The Remaining Days shows the remaining days until the expiration of the configuration. The expired configuration is shown as Finished in Remaining Days. The configurations that are defined without an End Date in order to have the configuration effective without any date limitation, the record is displayed as Unlimited.

have the configuration effective without any date limitation, the record is displayed as Unlimited.

- The eye-shaped icon allows users to show or hide columns, customizing the displayed data based on their needs.
- The Clear all filters clears all applied filters when needed.

> Note: Keep in mind! Expired records are automatically marked as Passive and cannot be reactivated.

How to define the scope of a Configuration?The first step in parameter configurations is selecting the scope source of the definition.At this stage, there are two options to proceed: Use 'Create Manually' to define configurations within the system, or 'Create with CSV' to bulk upload configurations with predefined data. Create Manually: Define the configuration by selecting the scope and defining the date range & parameter value.Create ManuallyThe Scope is formed by,Typing the required Codes (ProductCode, StoreCode, WarehouseCode, SupplierCode). The Codes are the codes that are provided in the master data. The codes can be defined with comma separators and can easily be pasted from CSV files.Selecting existing Groups created via the Product-Store Grouping screen with the help of the available groups listing dropdown. Product-Store Grouping screen  Create with CSV: Upload a .csv file containing the required details

. Product-Store Grouping screen  Create with CSV: Upload a .csv file containing the required details. The specific columns needed will depend on the selected scope (e.g., Product Code, Store Code). The sample CSV provides a template for required fields based on the selected scope. Create with CSVThe Scope is formed by,Entering the Group Codes that the system generates upon the Group creation in the Product-Store Grouping screen. The Group Name value in the created groups list of the Product-Store Grouping screen should be used in this column.Entering the Codes (ProductCode, StoreCode, WarehouseCode, SupplierCode) directly into the relevant scope option fields. The Codes are the codes that are provided in the master data. Note on Date Format: If the CSV includes date fields, ensure all date values follow the yyyy/mm/dd format

on Date Format: If the CSV includes date fields, ensure all date values follow the yyyy/mm/dd format. This prevents format-related errors during import and ensures consistency across all date-handling screens.- Once the required fields are completed, the "Next/Adjust Values" button is enabled, which will allow the user to continue with the parameter creation flow.
- To update the “Parameter Value” section, users can do so row by row or apply changes to all selected records using the Actions menu.
- If users want to add more scope combinations for the parameter, they can use the "Add New" option.
- If some of the scope combinations have to be deleted - since the scope option selection creates the cartesian product of the options -, the unnecessary scope combinations can be deleted with the Delete action in the Actions button.
- Once edits are complete, users can use the “Save the New Changes” option to finalize the updates.

- Once edits are complete, users can use the “Save the New Changes” option to finalize the updates.
- The saved parameter configurations are now ready for the next run.

## 1-Let’s start by comparing the rounded need and the target between yesterday and today.

It appears that both the rounded need and the target have increased. There could be several reasons, some of them:

1. The scope may have expanded.
2. The CoverPeriod Forecast may have risen.
3. The target cap parameters may have been modified.

Let’s begin with point 1, since it’s the simplest. We compared the `scope_with_supersede` data from yesterday’s regular run to today’s, and we found no significant differences.

So it is time to check forecast one,

It appears there is a large gap between yesterday’s and today’s cover-period forecasts, which is driving the increase in the target.

So two factors could be responsible:

1. Forecast values may have risen (though this seems unlikely, since only TMW shows an increase).
2. Cover Periods may have lengthened.

Now we’re evaluating option 2. To see if the Cover Period has increased, we’re quickly checking whether an additional-time parameter has been applied.

## Basics

| What? this screen holds | This screen lets users easily adjust key planning parameters to better maintain their strategic input data and support decision-making. |
| --- | --- |
| How? this screen works | Define adjustments using pre-set configuration options. Once the user applies a change, the system automatically updates the predictions and/or orders based on the new inputs for the next run. |
| Why? should I use this | To make it easier to track and adjust configuration settings without needing manual requests.It helps reduce effort for both clients and analysts by allowing direct updates to planning inputs in a faster, more streamlined way. |

## Parameters Configuration Features

Parameter Configurations:  This section allows users to manage all parameter settings. Users can view, filter, modify, export, or delete configurations. If needed, they can also activate or deactivate them based on business needs.

Configuration Detail: To review the details of a specific configuration, the user can select its Configuration ID to access comprehensive information, including parameter values, validity period, locations, and other attributes. If needed, they can make adjustments and save updates to ensure accuracy.

Create New Configuration: To create a new configuration, users can define key details such as scope, type, and validity period. Once set, they can fine-tune parameter values, apply bulk adjustments, and finalize updates to ensure seamless integration into the system.

values, apply bulk adjustments, and finalize updates to ensure seamless integration into the system.

Parameter Configurations This section gives users full visibility and control over their existing configurations. Users can filter, update, and manage all existing parameter configurations based on their planning needs, allowing faster decisions and better alignment across teams.

- Every configuration is distinguished by a unique Configuration ID, and each configuration is created regarding a Solution Type and a scope. The level of granularity of the configuration can be viewed from the Scope column. The details on the creator user of the configurations, last update, and creation times can also be viewed.
- The configurations are valid as long as the durations between the Start Date - End Date. Once the End Date passes, the configuration becomes Passive. Until after the End Date or unless a user deactivates the Configuration ID, the configuration remains Active. The activity duration can be checked from the Remaining Days column in the view.
- The Remaining Days shows the remaining days until the expiration of the configuration. The expired configuration is shown as Finished in Remaining Days. The configurations that are defined without an End Date in order to have the configuration effective without any date limitation, the record is displayed as Unlimited.

have the configuration effective without any date limitation, the record is displayed as Unlimited.

- To make further adjustments to the data, users can use the Actions menu for additional options.Users can export any configuration whenever needed. If a configuration is no longer required, users can delete it. Also, they can delete from the Actions column.
- The eye-shaped icon allows users to show or hide columns, customizing the displayed data based on their needs.
- The Clear all filters clears all applied filters when needed.

> Note: Keep in mind! Expired records are automatically marked as Passive and cannot be reactivated.

How to define the scope of a Configuration?The first step in parameter configurations is selecting the scope source of the definition.At this stage, there are two options to proceed: Use 'Create Manually' to define configurations within the system, or 'Create with CSV' to bulk upload configurations with predefined data. Create Manually: Define the configuration by selecting the scope and defining the date range & parameter value.Create ManuallyThe Scope is formed by,Typing the required Codes (ProductCode, StoreCode, WarehouseCode, SupplierCode). The Codes are the codes that are provided in the master data. The codes can be defined with comma separators and can easily be pasted from CSV files.Selecting existing Groups created via the Product-Store Grouping screen with the help of the available groups listing dropdown. Product-Store Grouping screen  Create with CSV: Upload a .csv file containing the required details

. Product-Store Grouping screen  Create with CSV: Upload a .csv file containing the required details. The specific columns needed will depend on the selected scope (e.g., Product Code, Store Code). The sample CSV provides a template for required fields based on the selected scope. Create with CSVThe Scope is formed by,Entering the Group Codes that the system generates upon the Group creation in the Product-Store Grouping screen. The Group Name value in the created groups list of the Product-Store Grouping screen should be used in this column.Entering the Codes (ProductCode, StoreCode, WarehouseCode, SupplierCode) directly into the relevant scope option fields. The Codes are the codes that are provided in the master data. Note on Date Format: When using date fields in the CSV, ensure that the values follow the yyyy-mm-dd format, as this is the standard sequence used in the system (year, month, day)

## The Types of Errors or Warnings

This section provides an overview of the system-generated warnings users may encounter while interacting with charts or editing data. These warnings are categorized as either informative or actionable, depending on whether they simply inform the user or require an action to proceed.

> Note: Actionable Warnings: Displayed when an input or action violates system rules. These warnings require users to make corrections before continuing.

Negative Value Entered for a Non-Negative Parameter:

Negative values can not be defined for non-negative parameters.

String Value Entered for a Numeric Parameter:

String values can not be defined for numeric parameters.

ing Value Entered for a Numeric Parameter:

String values can not be defined for numeric parameters.

> Note: Informative Warnings: Used to inform users about the system state or potential limitations. These warnings do not block the workflow but help maintain awareness.

Delete Selected Configurations:

Once the selected configurations are deleted, the action cannot be undone.

Configuration Status Change Restriction:

When a configuration is expired, the ID becomes passive as shown in the caption. These configurations can be reactivated by extending the End Date first.

CSV Import Rules for an Existing Configuration ID:

Uploading a CSV file will modify all parameters in a Configuration ID. Deleted items will be removed, new items will be added, and any changes to existing records will be updated. Unchanged values will remain the same.

e added, and any changes to existing records will be updated. Unchanged values will remain the same.

Invalid Data Type:
During CSV import, any field that requires an integer value must contain a valid integer. If a non-integer value is detected in these fields, the system will block the import and display an error specifying the affected row.

Unrecognized Entities in Uploaded File:
Data that does not exist in the system database cannot be processed.

## FAQ

- What happens if the user defines multiple configurations for an item-location? Which configuration’s value will be valid?

Each active configuration is taken into account for the UI parameter data input resolution process. There are a couple layers of rules for resolving the date range, duplications, overlapping dates, precedence among option levels.

rules for resolving the date range, duplications, overlapping dates, precedence among option levels.

The rule set outlines on the logic used to resolve parameter values for each product–store combination, by filtering relevant records, handling overlaps, and applying priority and overrides across different data sources and scope levels.

The scope combinations are resolved with respect to a priority sequence. For instance, defining a parameter on Product Code is more granular and specific that the ones defined from the Product Group option. Hence, Product Code and Store Code option overrides the ones defined on Product Code level. The most granular data overrides the least.

- For each distinct scope combination (item-based, location-based, or item-location-based), the system filters down to the most recently updated record if there are multiple candidates.
- There can be multiple records that match one of the following combinations:item + priority + start date + end datelocation + priority + start date + end dateitem + location + priority + start date + end date
- When duplicate records exist for any of these combinations, the system selects the one that was most recently updated (based on a Updated At timestamp).
- Records are filtered to include only those where the target date falls between start date and end date.
- Records are then aggregated or reduced down to the least granular level, specifically product–store level. That means if parameters are defined at broader levels (e.g., region or category), they’re eventually boiled down to specific product and store combinations.

.g., region or category), they’re eventually boiled down to specific product and store combinations.
- If multiple parameter records overlap due to overlapping date ranges, these are aggregated using a defined method (e.g., min, max, average, sum) to resolve conflicts.
- Parameters defined at different scope levels (e.g., Product, Store Group, Product Group + Warehouse) are resolved by sorting based on priority. The values with the lowest priority number (i.e., highest precedence) are selected.
- At the end of this process, each product–store pair has a resolved parameter value, and the system ensures that the most specific (i.e., most granular) configuration takes precedence, assuming it has the highest priority.

specific (i.e., most granular) configuration takes precedence, assuming it has the highest priority.
- If the parameter has another data source fed from the ETL process, the merge operation is made depending on the pre-configured rule: (1) override ETL values with UI definitions(2) use ETL values(3) merge both by a pre-defined aggregation method (e.g. min, max, average, sum)The override rules applies when a product - store has records on both sources (ETL and UI). If a product - store only has a parameter value on UI, the UI value is taken.
- This logic is about narrowing down parameter values to the most relevant and specific configuration for each product-store pair by filtering by date, resolving overlaps through aggregation, and applying priority-based rules to pick the final value.

This documentation outlines the key filters, underlying reasoning, and iterations applied during the seasonality modeling process. It aims to ensure transparency, consistency, and repeatability in future workflows.

## Challanges:

### 1- Staggered rollout:

Staggered rollout refers to a phased expansion in the number of stores where a product is made available. In many cases, this expansion happens abruptly — a product initially available in a limited set of stores is suddenly rolled out to a much larger network. This results in sharp stock increases that can be misinterpreted by the seasonality model as recurring seasonal demand patterns. As a consequence, these one-time distribution-driven spikes risk being learned and projected forward, potentially causing inflated demand forecasts in future cycles.

Exp:  `TMW_41BC_02`

### 2- Instock Levels:

lly causing inflated demand forecasts in future cycles.

Exp:  `TMW_41BC_02`

### 2- Instock Levels:

This challenge closely resembles the staggered rollout issue; however, instead of expanding the product to new stores, inventory is aggressively pushed to existing ones where the product is already listed. This sudden increase in stock levels often drives up sales temporarily, creating artificial spikes that distort the seasonality signal and lead to misleading future forecasts.

Exp: `KNG_V4PB_01`

### 3- New Class-colors:

nality signal and lead to misleading future forecasts.

Exp: `KNG_V4PB_01`

### 3- New Class-colors:

If a clas colorhas launched within the past year, the seasonality model often fails to capture a reliable seasonal pattern due to insufficient historical data. When the model attempts to forecast based on the class_color level trained on such limited data, it frequently results in inaccurate projections. Additionally, the initial months following a class color’s launch tend to exhibit high volatility that is not driven by seasonality, further compromising the quality of the signal and increasing the risk of misleading forecasts.

Exp : `JAB_20BL_90`

## Seasonality Implementations:

d increasing the risk of misleading forecasts.

Exp : `JAB_20BL_90`

## Seasonality Implementations:

1-Life Cycle Management:
As part of the Seasonality Data Preparation process, we exclude the first month of data for each product to avoid the volatile patterns typically seen right after launch. Additionally, we account for product inactivity: if a product remains unavailable in all stores for 9 months or more, we treat its return as a new lifecycle start. In such cases, we discard the first 2 months following its reactivation, along with any data that precedes the inactive period, to prevent outdated or misleading signals from affecting the seasonality model.

*Note: All Below rules has been writen to seasonality selection.*2-Clean Garbage Class Colors:

*Note: All Below rules has been writen to seasonality selection.*2-Clean Garbage Class Colors:

If a class_color has recorded fewer than 500 total sales across all stores in the past two years, we consider it too sparse and unreliable for learning meaningful seasonality patterns at its own level. In such cases, we intentionally force the seasonality selection to occur at higher hierarchy levels.

3-Staggered rollout finder:

For each class_color, we track the number of stores it is listed in on a monthly basis. If the store count increases by more than 40% or by more than 50 stores within any 6-month period, we flag it as a staggered rollout case. When such a flag is detected, we restrict the model from selecting seasonality at the class_color or group level.

4-Stock Rate:

, we restrict the model from selecting seasonality at the class_color or group level.

4-Stock Rate:

If a class_color’s average instock rate over the past year falls below 50%, we consider its sales data unreliable for capturing seasonality at that level. In such cases, we prevent the model from selecting seasonality at the class_color or group level.

5-New Class Color Finder :

If a class color has been introduced within the last year, we prevent the model from selecting seasonality at the class_color or group level

6-Monthly Instock Rate:

We expand the last 18 months of data for all products and calculate monthly instock rates for each class_color over the most recent 14 months. If a class_color falls below a 30% instock rate in any single month during this period, we consider its availability too inconsistent and restrict the model from selecting seasonality at the agg_level_6 level (Class_color).

For presentation stock inputs, those with a non-null end_date are fed into the raw data. In the raw data, the latest input value for each presentation stock (p-s) is retained. If an input has a non-null end_date, it is directly passed to Rocket.

Since Rocket’s resolve type is ui_first, priority is given to inputs with a non-null end_date.

If there are multiple inputs for different products within the same item family, Rocket uses the agg type = max, meaning it proceeds with the higher presentation stock value by default.
